{"title_page": "Bagley Junction, Wisconsin", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Boylston Junction, Wisconsin|timestamp=20200418010146|year=2020|month=April|day=18|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Boylston Junction, Wisconsin|date=18 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Bagley Junction, Wisconsin\n|settlement_type = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]] \n|nickname = \n|motto =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|image_map1 = \n|mapsize1 = \n|map_caption1 = \n|pushpin_map = Wisconsin#USA\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Wisconsin}}\n|subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Wisconsin|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Marinette County, Wisconsin|Marinette]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|leader_title1 = \n|leader_name1 = \n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  \n|area_footnotes = \n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|area_total_sq_mi = \n|area_land_sq_mi = \n|area_water_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of = \n|population_footnotes = \n|population_total = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone = [[Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset = -6\n|timezone_DST = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST = -5\n|elevation_footnotes = <ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|1577500|Bagley Junction, Wisconsin}}</ref>\n|elevation_m = \n|elevation_ft = 630\n|coordinates      = {{coord|45|08|18|N|87|45|04|W|region:US-WI|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code = [[Area codes 715 and 534|715 & 534]]\n|blank_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info = 1577500<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bagley Junction''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] located in the town of [[Porterfield, Wisconsin|Porterfield]], [[Marinette County, Wisconsin]], United States.<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Bagley Junction Wisconsin 1912.jpg|thumb|left|Bagley Junction, 1912 map detail]]\nBagley Junction is located on Bagley Road on the left bank of the [[Peshtigo River]], at the north end of the Potato Rapids Reservoir,<ref>{{cite book |title=Peshtigo River Multiple Project: Environmental Impact Statement |date=1997 |publisher=Federal Energy Regulatory Commission |location=Washington, DC |pages=3\u201342}}</ref><ref name=\"USGS\">''Porterfield Quadrangle, Wisconsin\u2014Marinette Co., 7.5-Minute Series (Topographic)''. 1982. Map, 1:24,000. Reston, VA: United States Department of the Interior Geological Survey.</ref> at an elevation of {{convert|630|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"gnis\"/> It is connected by road to [[Walsh, Wisconsin|Walsh]] to the north, [[Porterfield (community), Wisconsin|Porterfield]] to the west (via Grasser Road), [[Peshtigo, Wisconsin|Peshtigo]] to the south (via Right of Way Road), and [[Marinette, Wisconsin|Marinette]] to the east (via [[Wisconsin Highway 64]]).\n\n==Name==\nBagley Junction is named for John Bagley (June 20, 1852 [[Quebec]] &ndash; August 17, 1920 [[Tacoma, Washington]]),<ref name = \"obit\">\"John Bagley\" (obituary). ''Chicago Lumberman'' 39, page 45.</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/N3G8-V8L Washington Death Certificates, 1907\u20131960]</ref> a lumberman.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Callary|first1=Edward|title=Place Names of Wisconsin|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, WI|isbn=978-0-299-30964-0|page=19}}</ref><ref>Lalk, E. A. 1922. \"The Ranier National Park Branch.\" [http://milwaukeeroadarchives.com/MilwaukeeRoadMagazine/1922JuneMiltClark.pdf ''The Milwaukee Employes' Magazine''] (sic), June: 12\u201315. Page 12.</ref> After his early activity in Wisconsin, Bagley was active in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and later became president of the [[Tacoma Eastern Railroad]].<ref name = \"obit\"/> There is another Bagley Junction, also named after John Bagley, in [[King County, Washington]].<ref>{{cite gnis|1516037|Bagley Junction, Washington}}</ref><ref>''North Bend Quadrangle, Washington\u2014King Co., 7.5-Minute Series (Topographic)''. 1953. Map, 1:24,000. Denver, CO: U. S. Geological Survey.</ref>\n\n==History==\nBagley Junction was inhabited by [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] before the arrival of white settlers. Four oval [[tumulus|burial mounds]] known as the Bagley Junction Mounds were mapped by Harvey Younger in 1913.<ref name=\"Kuehn\">{{cite journal |last1=Kuehn |first1=Steven R. |title=Archaeology around Wisconsin |journal=The Wisconsin Archaeologist |date=2007 |volume=88 |issue=2 |page=148}}</ref> Shell content indicates that the mounds were formed from soil taken from the bank of Peshtigo River.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Titus |first1=William A. |title=History of the Fox River Valley, Lake Winnebago, and the Green Bay Region |date=1930 |publisher=S.J. Clarke Publishing Company |location=Chicago |page=44}}</ref> The mounds may be associated with a [[Woodland period#Late Woodland period (500\u20131000 CE)|Late Woodland]] habitation.<ref name=\"Kuehn\"/> The burial mounds were further investigated in 2007 during an archaeological survey for a road project. The survey identified two mounds about {{convert|75|ft|sp=us}} apart between Bagley Road and the Peshtigo River; the southern mound measures {{convert|30|x|18.5|ft|sp=us}} and is about {{convert|15|in|sp=us}} high, and the northern mound measures {{convert|22|x|19|ft|sp=us}} and is about {{convert|18|in|sp=us}} high. There is no surface evidence of the other two mounds mapped in 1913; it is believed they were destroyed by a former driveway that is now used as a snowmobile trail.<ref name=\"Kuehn\"/>\n\nIn 1894, the Wisconsin & Michigan Railway opened an office<ref>{{cite news |title=A large and fine new locomotive ... |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063734/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Neenah Daily Times |date=June 11, 1894 |page=4 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> and established workshops at Bagley Junction, employing up to sixty men.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Wisconsin & Michigan Railroad |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49062707/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Centralia Enterprise and Tribune |date=September 1, 1894 |page=8 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> That year the company also erected coal sheds and water tanks at the site.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Wisconsin & Michigan Railway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063907/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Journal Times |date=May 12, 1894 |page=4 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> From 1894 to 1938, the site was a railroad junction for a line that ran north to Walsh and onward to [[Iron Mountain, Michigan]].<ref name=\"McLeod\">{{cite journal |last1=McLeod |first1=Richard |title=History of the Wisconsin and Michigan Railway |journal=The Railway and Locomotive Historical Society Bulletin |date=1968 |volume=118 |pages=7\u201320}}</ref> The line was built using surplus rail from the [[World's Columbian Exposition|Chicago World's Fair]], which had closed in 1893.<ref>{{cite book |last1= King |first1= Beverly |first2= Dan |last2= Deacon |lastauthoramp= yes |year= 1987 |title= Faithorn Centennial, 1887\u20131987 |location= Faithorn, MI |publisher= Author |page=13}}</ref> The line to Walsh was removed in 1938,<ref name=\"McLeod\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Seek Permission to Abandon Lines |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34483265/bagley_junction_wi/ |newspaper=The Oshkosh Northwestern |date=April 10, 1937 |page=17 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate = August 2, 2019}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Approve Wisconsin and Michigan Ry. Line Abandonment |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34483329/bagley_junction_wi/ |newspaper=The Daily Tribune |date=January 20, 1938 |page=5 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate = August 2, 2019}} {{Open access}}</ref> but an east-west branch line belonging to the former [[Milwaukee Road]] still exists.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Official Guide of the Railways]]|date=June 1941|publisher=National Railway Publishing Company|location=[[New York City]]}}</ref> The track is currently owned by [[Escanaba and Lake Superior Railroad]].<ref>{{cite map|title=Wisconsin Railroads & Harbors 2020|author=[[Wisconsin Department of Transportation]]|date=January 2020|url=https://wisconsindot.gov/Documents/travel/rail/railmap.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century a lumber camp and sawmill operated in Bagley Junction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alfred Rudolph |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063457/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The La Crosse Tribune |date=November 18, 1908 |page=8 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Steal Machines from Sawmills |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49062237/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Post-Crescent |date=September 16, 1920 |page=6 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> In the 1920s, Andrew Jackson Smith (1832\u20131929), a resident of the community and a Civil War veteran, was jocularly known as the \"mayor\" of Bagley Junction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrew J. Smith |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49064304/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The Sheboygan Press |date=August 17, 1926 |page=6 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two More Marinette G.A.R. Members Die |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49065219/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The La Crosse Tribune |date=December 4, 1929 |page=2 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bagley Junction 'Mayor' Is Buried |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49064266/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The Sheboygan Press |date=December 5, 1929 |page=13 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Bagley Junction, Wisconsin}}\n\n{{Adjacent stations|system=Milwaukee Road|line=Crivitz-Menominee|left=Porterfield|right=Marinette}}\n\n{{Marinette County, Wisconsin}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Marinette County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Former Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad stations]]\n\n\n{{MarinetteCountyWI-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Boylston Junction, Wisconsin|timestamp=20200418010146|year=2020|month=April|day=18|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Boylston Junction, Wisconsin|date=18 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Bagley Junction, Wisconsin\n|settlement_type = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated community]] \n|nickname = \n|motto =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|image_map1 = \n|mapsize1 = \n|map_caption1 = \n|pushpin_map = Wisconsin#USA\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Wisconsin}}\n|subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Wisconsin|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Marinette County, Wisconsin|Marinette]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|leader_title1 = \n|leader_name1 = \n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  \n|area_footnotes = \n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|area_total_sq_mi = \n|area_land_sq_mi = \n|area_water_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of = \n|population_footnotes = \n|population_total = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone = [[Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset = -6\n|timezone_DST = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST = -5\n|elevation_footnotes = <ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|1577500|Bagley Junction, Wisconsin}}</ref>\n|elevation_m = \n|elevation_ft = 630\n|coordinates      = {{coord|45|08|18|N|87|45|04|W|region:US-WI|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code = [[Area codes 715 and 534|715 & 534]]\n|blank_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info = 1577500<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bagley Junction''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] located in the town of [[Porterfield, Wisconsin|Porterfield]], [[Marinette County, Wisconsin]], United States.<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Bagley Junction Wisconsin 1912.jpg|thumb|left|Bagley Junction, 1912 map detail]]\nBagley Junction is located on Bagley Road on the left bank of the [[Peshtigo River]], at the north end of the Potato Rapids Reservoir,<ref>{{cite book |title=Peshtigo River Multiple Project: Environmental Impact Statement |date=1997 |publisher=Federal Energy Regulatory Commission |location=Washington, DC |pages=3\u201342}}</ref><ref name=\"USGS\">''Porterfield Quadrangle, Wisconsin\u2014Marinette Co., 7.5-Minute Series (Topographic)''. 1982. Map, 1:24,000. Reston, VA: United States Department of the Interior Geological Survey.</ref> at an elevation of {{convert|630|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"gnis\"/> It is connected by road to [[Walsh, Wisconsin|Walsh]] to the north, [[Porterfield (community), Wisconsin|Porterfield]] to the west (via Grasser Road), [[Peshtigo, Wisconsin|Peshtigo]] to the south (via Right of Way Road), and [[Marinette, Wisconsin|Marinette]] to the east (via [[Wisconsin Highway 64]]).\n\n==Name==\nBagley Junction is named for John Bagley (June 20, 1852 [[Quebec]] &ndash; August 17, 1920 [[Tacoma, Washington]]),<ref name = \"obit\">\"John Bagley\" (obituary). ''Chicago Lumberman'' 39, page 45.</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/N3G8-V8L Washington Death Certificates, 1907\u20131960]</ref> a lumberman.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Callary|first1=Edward|title=Place Names of Wisconsin|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, WI|isbn=978-0-299-30964-0|page=19}}</ref><ref>Lalk, E. A. 1922. \"The Ranier National Park Branch.\" [http://milwaukeeroadarchives.com/MilwaukeeRoadMagazine/1922JuneMiltClark.pdf ''The Milwaukee Employes' Magazine''] (sic), June: 12\u201315. Page 12.</ref> After his early activity in Wisconsin, Bagley was active in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and later became president of the [[Tacoma Eastern Railroad]].<ref name = \"obit\"/> There is another Bagley Junction, also named after John Bagley, in [[King County, Washington]].<ref>{{cite gnis|1516037|Bagley Junction, Washington}}</ref><ref>''North Bend Quadrangle, Washington\u2014King Co., 7.5-Minute Series (Topographic)''. 1953. Map, 1:24,000. Denver, CO: U. S. Geological Survey.</ref>\n\n==History==\nBagley Junction was inhabited by [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] before the arrival of white settlers. Four oval [[tumulus|burial mounds]] known as the Bagley Junction Group were mapped by Harvey Younger in 1913.<ref name=\"Kuehn\">{{cite journal |last1=Kuehn |first1=Steven R. |title=Archaeology around Wisconsin |journal=The Wisconsin Archaeologist |date=2007 |volume=88 |issue=2 |page=148}}</ref> Shell content indicates that the mounds were formed from soil taken from the bank of Peshtigo River.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Titus |first1=William A. |title=History of the Fox River Valley, Lake Winnebago, and the Green Bay Region |date=1930 |publisher=S.J. Clarke Publishing Company |location=Chicago |page=44}}</ref> The mounds may be associated with a [[Woodland period#Late Woodland period (500\u20131000 CE)|Late Woodland]] habitation.<ref name=\"Kuehn\"/> The burial mounds were further investigated in 2007 during an archaeological survey for a road project. The survey identified two mounds about {{convert|75|ft|sp=us}} apart between Bagley Road and the Peshtigo River; the southern mound measures {{convert|30|x|18.5|ft|sp=us}} and is about {{convert|15|in|sp=us}} high, and the northern mound measures {{convert|22|x|19|ft|sp=us}} and is about {{convert|18|in|sp=us}} high. There is no surface evidence of the other two mounds mapped in 1913; it is believed they were destroyed by a former driveway that is now used as a snowmobile trail.<ref name=\"Kuehn\"/>\n\nIn 1894, the Wisconsin & Michigan Railway opened an office<ref>{{cite news |title=A large and fine new locomotive ... |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063734/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Neenah Daily Times |date=June 11, 1894 |page=4 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> and established workshops at Bagley Junction, employing up to sixty men.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Wisconsin & Michigan Railroad |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49062707/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Centralia Enterprise and Tribune |date=September 1, 1894 |page=8 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> That year the company also erected coal sheds and water tanks at the site.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Wisconsin & Michigan Railway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063907/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Journal Times |date=May 12, 1894 |page=4 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> From 1894 to 1938, the site was a railroad junction for a line that ran north to Walsh and onward to [[Iron Mountain, Michigan]].<ref name=\"McLeod\">{{cite journal |last1=McLeod |first1=Richard |title=History of the Wisconsin and Michigan Railway |journal=The Railway and Locomotive Historical Society Bulletin |date=1968 |volume=118 |pages=7\u201320}}</ref> The line was built using surplus rail from the [[World's Columbian Exposition|Chicago World's Fair]], which had closed in 1893.<ref>{{cite book |last1= King |first1= Beverly |first2= Dan |last2= Deacon |lastauthoramp= yes |year= 1987 |title= Faithorn Centennial, 1887\u20131987 |location= Faithorn, MI |publisher= Author |page=13}}</ref> The line to Walsh was removed in 1938,<ref name=\"McLeod\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Seek Permission to Abandon Lines |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34483265/bagley_junction_wi/ |newspaper=The Oshkosh Northwestern |date=April 10, 1937 |page=17 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate = August 2, 2019}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Approve Wisconsin and Michigan Ry. Line Abandonment |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34483329/bagley_junction_wi/ |newspaper=The Daily Tribune |date=January 20, 1938 |page=5 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate = August 2, 2019}} {{Open access}}</ref> but an east-west branch line belonging to the former [[Milwaukee Road]] still exists.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Official Guide of the Railways]]|date=June 1941|publisher=National Railway Publishing Company|location=[[New York City]]}}</ref> The track is currently owned by [[Escanaba and Lake Superior Railroad]].<ref>{{cite map|title=Wisconsin Railroads & Harbors 2020|author=[[Wisconsin Department of Transportation]]|date=January 2020|url=https://wisconsindot.gov/Documents/travel/rail/railmap.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century a lumber camp and sawmill operated in Bagley Junction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alfred Rudolph |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49063457/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The La Crosse Tribune |date=November 18, 1908 |page=8 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Steal Machines from Sawmills |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49062237/bagley-junction/ |newspaper=The Post-Crescent |date=September 16, 1920 |page=6 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> In the 1920s, Andrew Jackson Smith (1832\u20131929), a resident of the community and a Civil War veteran, was jocularly known as the \"mayor\" of Bagley Junction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrew J. Smith |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49064304/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The Sheboygan Press |date=August 17, 1926 |page=6 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two More Marinette G.A.R. Members Die |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49065219/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The La Crosse Tribune |date=December 4, 1929 |page=2 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bagley Junction 'Mayor' Is Buried |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49064266/andrew-smith-1832-1929/ |newspaper=The Sheboygan Press |date=December 5, 1929 |page=13 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n=