{"title_page": "Google Duo", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Google Duo\n| logo                   = Google Duo icon.svg\n| logo size              = \n| screenshot             = <center>[[File:Google Duo.png|frameless|center]]</center>\n| caption                = A screenshot of Duo\n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Google|Google LLC]]\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2016|08|16}}\n| ver layout             = stacked\n| discontinued           = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Android (operating system)|Android]]&nbsp;4.1 or later\n*[[iOS]]&nbsp;9.0 or later\n}}\n| platform =\n| size                   = \n| language               = [[English language|English]]\n| genre                  = [[Videotelephony|Video chat]] [[mobile app]]\n| license                = \n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|https://duo.google.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Google Duo''' is a [[Videotelephony|video chat]] [[mobile app]] developed by [[Google]], available on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] operating systems. It was announced at [[Google I/O|Google's developer conference]] on May 18, 2016, and began its worldwide release on August 16, 2016. It is also available to use via Google's [[Google Chrome|Chrome]] [[web browser]] on [[desktop computer|desktop]] and [[laptop]] computers.\n\nGoogle Duo<ref>Google duo, https://www.canarey.in/2020/04/google-duo-for-pc.html, 20 April 2020</ref> lets users make video calls in [[High-definition video|high definition]]. It is optimized for low-[[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] networks. [[End-to-end encryption]] is enabled by default. Duo is based on phone numbers, allowing users to call someone from their contact list. The app automatically switches between [[Wi-Fi]] and [[cellular network]]s. A \"Knock Knock\" feature lets users see a live preview of the caller before answering. An update in April 2017 lets users worldwide make audio-only calls.\n\nIn an email sent to Android phone manufacturers on October 5, 2016, Google announced that, starting December 1, 2016, Google Duo replaced [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]]<ref>Google Hangouts, https://www.canarey.in/2020/04/google-hangouts-dark-mode.html, 20 April 2020</ref> within the suite of Google apps Android phone makers must pre-install on devices, with Hangouts instead becoming an optional app for phone makers.<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Ruddock |title=Google is demoting Hangouts to \"optional\" in the Google Apps package for Android, to be replaced by Duo |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2016/10/07/google-is-demoting-hangouts-to-optional-in-the-google-apps-package-for-android-to-be-replaced-by-duo/ |website=9to5google |date=October 7, 2016 |accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nGoogle Duo video calls are in [[720p]] [[High-definition video|HD video]].<ref name=\"Features\">{{cite web |first1=Amit |last1=Fulay |first2=Yariv |last2=Adan |title=Saying \ud83d\udc4b to Allo and Duo: new apps for smart messaging and video calling |url=https://blog.google/products/allo/allo-duo-apps-messaging-video/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 18, 2016 |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> It is optimized for low-[[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] mobile networks through [[WebRTC]] and uses [[QUIC]] over [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]]. Optimization is further achieved through the degradation of video quality through monitoring network quality.<ref name=\"Announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/18/11690728/google-duo-video-call-app-vs-apple-facetime-io-2016|title=Google Duo makes mobile video calls fast and simple|last=Bohn|first=Dieter|date=May 18, 2016|website=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> \"Knock Knock\" shows a live preview of the caller before the recipient picks up, which Google says is to \"make calls feel more like an invitation rather than an interruption\".<ref name=\"Release\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.google/products/duo/meet-google-duo-simple-1-to-1-video/|title=Meet Google Duo, a simple 1-to-1 video calling app for everyone|last=Uberti|first=Justin|date=August 16, 2016|website=The Keyword Google Blog|publisher=[[Google]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> [[End-to-end encryption]] is enabled by default.<ref name=\"Features\"/> Duo is based on phone numbers, allowing users to call people from their contact list.<ref name=\"Features\"/> The app automatically switches between [[Wi-Fi]] and [[cellular network]]s.<ref name=\"Features\"/> For [[packet loss concealment]] Duo uses WaveNetEQ, a [[generative model]] based on [[DeepMind]]/[[Google AI]]\u2019s [[DeepMind#WaveNet and successors|WaveRNN]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ai.googleblog.com/2020/04/improving-audio-quality-in-duo-with.html|title=Improving Audio Quality in Duo with WaveNetEQ|website=Google AI Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2017, it was announced that Google Duo would let users make audio-only calls. The feature was first launched in Brazil,<ref>{{cite web |first=Mario |last=Queiroz |title=Google for Brazil: Building a more inclusive internet for everyone, everywhere |url=https://blog.google/topics/internet-access/google-brazil-building-more-inclusive-internet-everyone-everywhere/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nikki |last=Erlick |title=Google announces app updates to Allo, Duo, and Photos |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/22/15024736/google-allo-duo-photos-updates-announced |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Palmer |title=Google Duo is finally getting an audio-only call option, rolling out first in Brazil [APK Download] |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/03/22/google-duo-finally-getting-audio-call-option-rolling-first-brazil/ |website=Android Police |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> with a global rollout in April.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google Duo's voice calls are now available worldwide |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/10/15242416/voice-calling-google-duo-worldwide |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA year later in March 2018, video and voice messages were added to Duo. Users can leave messages up to 30 seconds long for contacts who are unavailable. These messages can then be viewed by the other party, with the option of calling afterwards.<ref name=\"duo-video-voice-messages\">{{cite web|last1=Lindsay|first1=Dave|title=Miss a call\u2014but not the moment\u2014with video messages on Google Duo|url=https://blog.google/products/duo/miss-call-not-moment-video-messages-google-duo/|website=The Keyword Google Blog|accessdate=March 15, 2018|date=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSupport for eight-person video calls in both the iOS and Android versions of the app was added in May 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=juberti |number=1131685391545786369 |date=May 23, 2019 |title=#GoogleDuo group calling is now fully deployed, with the simplicity, quality, and security you expect from Duo.}}</ref> In line with similar group calling offerings from [[FaceTime]], [[WhatsApp]], [[Skype]] and [[Facebook Messenger]], participants can join or leave the conversation at any time.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Google Allo]]\n* [[Google Hangouts]]\n* [[List of video telecommunication services and product brands]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://duo.google.com/}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n[[Category:Google software|Duo]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:iOS software]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:2016 software]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Google Duo\n| logo                   = Google Duo icon.svg\n| logo size              = \n| screenshot             = <center>[[File:Google Duo.png|frameless|center]]</center>\n| caption                = A screenshot of Duo\n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Google|Google LLC]]\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2016|08|16}}\n| ver layout             = stacked\n| discontinued           = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Android (operating system)|Android]]&nbsp;4.1 or later\n*[[iOS]]&nbsp;9.0 or later\n}}\n| platform =\n| size                   = \n| language               = [[English language|English]]\n| genre                  = [[Videotelephony|Video chat]] [[mobile app]]\n| license                = \n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|https://duo.google.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Google Duo''' is a [[Videotelephony|video chat]] [[mobile app]] developed by [[Google]], available on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] operating systems. It was announced at [[Google I/O|Google's developer conference]] on May 18, 2016, and began its worldwide release on August 16, 2016. It is also available to use via Google's [[Google Chrome|Chrome]] [[web browser]] on [[desktop computer|desktop]] and [[laptop]] computers.\n\nGoogle Duo lets users make video calls in [[High-definition video|high definition]]. It is optimized for low-[[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] networks. [[End-to-end encryption]] is enabled by default. Duo is based on phone numbers, allowing users to call someone from their contact list. The app automatically switches between [[Wi-Fi]] and [[cellular network]]s. A \"Knock Knock\" feature lets users see a live preview of the caller before answering. An update in April 2017 lets users worldwide make audio-only calls.\n\nIn an email sent to Android phone manufacturers on October 5, 2016, Google announced that, starting December 1, 2016, Google Duo replaced [[Google Hangouts|Hangouts]] within the suite of Google apps Android phone makers must pre-install on devices, with Hangouts instead becoming an optional app for phone makers.<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Ruddock |title=Google is demoting Hangouts to \"optional\" in the Google Apps package for Android, to be replaced by Duo |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2016/10/07/google-is-demoting-hangouts-to-optional-in-the-google-apps-package-for-android-to-be-replaced-by-duo/ |website=9to5google |date=October 7, 2016 |accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nGoogle Duo video calls are in [[720p]] [[High-definition video|HD video]].<ref name=\"Features\">{{cite web |first1=Amit |last1=Fulay |first2=Yariv |last2=Adan |title=Saying \ud83d\udc4b to Allo and Duo: new apps for smart messaging and video calling |url=https://blog.google/products/allo/allo-duo-apps-messaging-video/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=May 18, 2016 |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> It is optimized for low-[[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] mobile networks through [[WebRTC]] and uses [[QUIC]] over [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]]. Optimization is further achieved through the degradation of video quality through monitoring network quality.<ref name=\"Announcement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/18/11690728/google-duo-video-call-app-vs-apple-facetime-io-2016|title=Google Duo makes mobile video calls fast and simple|last=Bohn|first=Dieter|date=May 18, 2016|website=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> \"Knock Knock\" shows a live preview of the caller before the recipient picks up, which Google says is to \"make calls feel more like an invitation rather than an interruption\".<ref name=\"Release\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.google/products/duo/meet-google-duo-simple-1-to-1-video/|title=Meet Google Duo, a simple 1-to-1 video calling app for everyone|last=Uberti|first=Justin|date=August 16, 2016|website=The Keyword Google Blog|publisher=[[Google]]|accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> [[End-to-end encryption]] is enabled by default.<ref name=\"Features\"/> Duo is based on phone numbers, allowing users to call people from their contact list.<ref name=\"Features\"/> The app automatically switches between [[Wi-Fi]] and [[cellular network]]s.<ref name=\"Features\"/> For [[packet loss concealment]] Duo uses WaveNetEQ, a [[generative model]] based on [[DeepMind]]/[[Google AI]]\u2019s [[DeepMind#WaveNet and successors|WaveRNN]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ai.googleblog.com/2020/04/improving-audio-quality-in-duo-with.html|title=Improving Audio Quality in Duo with WaveNetEQ|website=Google AI Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2017, it was announced that Google Duo would let users make audio-only calls. The feature was first launched in Brazil,<ref>{{cite web |first=Mario |last=Queiroz |title=Google for Brazil: Building a more inclusive internet for everyone, everywhere |url=https://blog.google/topics/internet-access/google-brazil-building-more-inclusive-internet-everyone-everywhere/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nikki |last=Erlick |title=Google announces app updates to Allo, Duo, and Photos |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/22/15024736/google-allo-duo-photos-updates-announced |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Palmer |title=Google Duo is finally getting an audio-only call option, rolling out first in Brazil [APK Download] |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/03/22/google-duo-finally-getting-audio-call-option-rolling-first-brazil/ |website=Android Police |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> with a global rollout in April.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google Duo's voice calls are now available worldwide |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/10/15242416/voice-calling-google-duo-worldwide |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA year later in March 2018, video and voice messages were added to Duo. Users can leave messages up to 30 seconds long for contacts who are unavailable. These messages can then be viewed by the other party, with the option of calling afterwards.<ref name=\"duo-video-voice-messages\">{{cite web|last1=Lindsay|first1=Dave|title=Miss a call\u2014but not the moment\u2014with video messages on Google Duo|url=https://blog.google/products/duo/miss-call-not-moment-video-messages-google-duo/|website=The Keyword Google Blog|accessdate=March 15, 2018|date=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSupport for eight-person video calls in both the iOS and Android versions of the app was added in May 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=juberti |number=1131685391545786369 |date=May 23, 2019 |title=#GoogleDuo group calling is now fully deployed, with the simplicity, quality, and security you expect from Duo.}}</ref> In line with similar group calling offerings from [[FaceTime]], [[WhatsApp]], [[Skype]] and [[Facebook Messenger]], participants can join or leave the conversation at any time.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Google Allo]]\n* [[Google Hangouts]]\n* [[List of video telecommunication services and product brands]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://duo.google.com/}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n[[Category:Google software|Duo]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:iOS software]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:2016 software]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n", "name_user": "Iamits", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Duo"}
{"title_page": "Lee Nak-yeon", "text_new": "{{short description|Prime Minister of South Korea}}\n{{Korean name|Lee}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|name          = Lee Nak-yeon\n| native_name = {{nobold|\uc774\ub099\uc5f0}}\n| native_name_lang = ko\n|image         = South Korean Prime Minister Lee - 2017 (36235112603) (cropped).jpg\n|office2        = 41st [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]\n|president2     = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n|term_start2    = 31 May 2017\n|term_end2      = 14 January 2020\n|deputy2        = [[Kim Dong-yeon]]<br>[[Kim Sang-gon]]<br>[[Yoo Eun-hae]]<br>[[Hong Nam-ki]]\n|predecessor2   = [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]<br>[[Yoo Il-ho]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|successor2     = [[Chung Sye-kyun]]\n|office3        = [[Governor of South Jeolla Province]]\n|term_start3    = 1 July 2014\n|term_end3      = 10 May 2017\n|predecessor3   = Park Jun-young\n|successor3     = [[Kim Yung-rok]]\n|office         = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Korea|National Assembly]] <br>{{small|Elect}}\n|term_label     = Assuming office\n|term           = 30 May 2020\n|predecessor    = [[Chung Sye-kyun]]\n|successor      = \n|constituency   = [[Jongno-gu]]\n|term_start1    = 30 May 2000\n|term_end1      = 15 May 2014\n|predecessor1   = Kim In-gon\n|successor1     = Lee Gae-ho\n|constituency1  = [[Damyang County|Damyang]], [[Hampyeong County|Hampyeong]], [[Yeonggwang County|Yeonggwang]] and [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|12|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Yeonggwang County|Yeonggwang]], [[South Korea]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n|spouse         = [[Kim Suk-hee]]\n|children       = 1\n|signature      = Signature of Lee Nak-yeon.png\n|education      = [[Seoul National University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul = {{linktext|\uc774|\ub099|\uc5f0}}\n|hanja  = {{linktext|\u674e|\u6d1b|\u6df5}}\n|rr     = I Nak-yeon \n|mr     = Yi Nag-y\u014fn\n}}\n'''Lee Nak-yeon''' ({{korean|hangul=\uc774\ub099\uc5f0|hanja=\u674e\u6d1b\u6df5}}; born 20 December 1951),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star-profile.tistory.com/m/85|title=\uad6d\ubb34\ucd1d\ub9ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0 \ud504\ub85c\ud544|date=15 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.tip.daum.net/question/88036592|title=\uc804\ub0a8\ub3c4\uc9c0\uc0ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0\uc740 \uad6d\uc778\uc5d0\ub2f9\uc778\uac00??|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.co.kr/news/300049|title=\ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ub2f9\uc120 \ud6c4 \ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \uc815\ubd80 \uc774\ub099\uc5f0 \uc804\ub0a8\uc9c0\uc0ac \ucd1d\ub9ac \ub0b4\uc815 \uc131\ud5a5\uc740?|first=|last=\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4\ucc9c\ud22c\ub370\uc774|date=10 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref> also known as Lee Nak-yon, is a [[South Korea]]n politician who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of South Korea|41st]] [[Prime Minister of South Korea]].<ref name=\"ref1\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.arirang.co.kr/News/News_View.asp?nseq=203843|title=Korea's new president announces key Cabinet picks|website=Arirang|access-date=May 11, 2017}}</ref> He is also the longest serving prime minister of South Korea since the [[Constitution of South Korea]] was last revised in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191028001800315|title=Lee becomes longest-serving prime minister in S. Korea|last=\uae40\uc218\uc5f0|date=2019-10-28|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> He previously served as the governor of [[Jeollanam-do]] province.<ref name=ref1>{{cite web|language=Korean |url=http://mbn.mk.co.kr/pages/news/newsView.php?category=mbn00006&news_seq_no=3218706 |title=\u6587\ub300\ud1b5\ub839, \uad6d\ubb34\ucd1d\ub9ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0\u00b7\uad6d\uc815\uc6d0\uc7a5 \uc11c\ud6c8\u00b7\ube44\uc11c\uc2e4\uc7a5 \uc784\uc885\uc11d\u00b7\uacbd\ud638\uc2e4\uc7a5 \uc8fc\uc601\ud6c8 \uc9c0\uba85 |publisher=Mbn.mk.co.kr |date=2017-05-10 |accessdate=2017-05-10}}</ref> Before serving as governor, he worked as a journalist for the ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' and served as a member of the [[National Assembly of Korea|National Assembly]] for four terms.\n\n== Early life and education==\nLee was born on December 20, 1951 in [[Yeonggwang County]] in [[South Jeolla Province]]. After graduating from [[Seoul National University]] with a degree in law, he worked as a journalist for the daily ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' newspaper until 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/05/11/2017051101354.html|title=Moon Taps South Jeolla Province Governor as New PM|access-date=2017-05-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nHe entered politics in 2000 \"based on his ties with former President [[Kim Dae-jung]] he formed while covering politics.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/05/10/0200000000AEN20170510004251315.html|title=(LEAD) (profile) Moon's premier pick is based in liberal stronghold, has broad political ties|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=2017-05-11|language=en}}</ref> Following his departure from the ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' he was elected as a member of the [[National Assembly of Korea|National Assembly]] in 2000 and served for four terms.<ref name=\":0\" /> He also served as a spokesman for former President [[Roh Moo-hyun]] when he was the president-elect in 2002.<ref name=\"Korea\">[http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pad/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=229097 \"S. Jeolla governor tapped as PM nominee\"], Korea Times, May 10, 2017 .</ref>\n\nHe left office in the middle of his fourth term in 2014 to successfully run for governor of [[South Jeolla Province]].\n\n== Prime Minister ==\nOn May 10, 2017, he was nominated by [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] to be the next [[Prime Minister of South Korea]], succeeding [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]. He left office as governor of the South Jeolla Province on the same day.\nHe is seen as having close ties with key Japanese politicians, having served many years as a senior officer in the [[Japan-Korea Parliamentarians' Union|Korea-Japan Parliamentarians' Union]]. Lee speaks fluent Japanese.<ref name=\"Nikkei\">[http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/South-Korean-prime-minister-pick-seen-as-point-man-on-Japan \"South Korean prime minister pick seen as point man on Japan\"], Nikkei Asian Review, May 11, 2017 .</ref> On June 25, Prime Minister Lee urged North Korea to release their prisoners. On July 27, Prime Minister Lee Nak-yeon, who is known to be knowledgeable about Japan, criticized the accord regarding \u2018comfort women\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20170727/p2a/00m/0na/017000c|title=Japan wary of S. Korea's growing opposition to 'comfort women' accord|date=27 July 2017|publisher=|via=Mainichi Daily News}}</ref> On August 16, Lee reacted negatively to calls for South Korea to possess nuclear weapons, saying the move would undermine Seoul's calls for North Korea to denuclearize, trigger a nuclear arms race and put the country under international sanctions. Reflecting such calls, the main opposition Liberty Korea Party adopted a demand for the redeployment of US tactical nuclear arms as its official party line during a general meeting of its lawmakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170816000831#cb|title=PM negative about calls for Korea\u2018s nuclear armament|date=16 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On November 29, Lee raised concerns that cryptocurrencies were corrupting the youth of South Korea, remarking \u201cThere are cases in which young Koreans including students are jumping in to make quick money and virtual currencies are used in illegal activities like drug dealing or multi-level marketing for frauds\u201d.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Post-PM career ==\nIn [[2020 South Korean legislative election|2020 election]], Lee stood for [[Jongno District|Jongno]] constituency and defeated the [[United Future Party|UFP]] President [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 15 April 2020|title= [\ub2f9\uc120-\uc11c\uc6b8 \uc885\ub85c] \uc774\ub099\uc5f0, \u201c\uad6d\ub09c \uadf9\ubcf5\uc5d0 \ud63c\uc2e0 \ub178\ub825 \ud560 \uac83\u201d|url= http://cnews.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=202004152325409437d9fbed771_16|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!Year\n!Province\n!Party Affiliation\n!Votes \n!Percentage of votes\n!Results\n|-\n|16th National Assembly General Election\n|2000\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party (2000)]]\n|37,863\n|60.20%\n|Won\n|-\n|17th National Assembly General Election\n|2004\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party (2000)]]\n|30,123\n|55.28%\n|Won\n|-\n|18th National Assembly General Election\n|2008\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yougggwang, [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]] Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2008)|Democratic Party (2008)]] \n|42,950\n|67.93%\n|Won\n|-\n|19th National Assembly General Election\n|2012\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Damyang County|Damyang]], [[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang, [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]] Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic United Party]] \n|63,887\n|77.32%\n|Won\n|-\n|Provincial Gubernatorial Election \n|2014\n|[[South Jeolla Province|South Jeolla]] \n|[[New Politics Alliance for Democracy]] (NPAD)\n|755,036\n|77.96%\n|Won\n|-\n|21st National Assembly General Election\n|2020\n|[[Seoul|Jongno]]\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|54,902\n|58.38%\n|Won\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nLee is married. Lee Nak-yon's bongwan belongs to the Jeonju Yi clan, which makes him part of the royal Yi family. He is also the 22nd-generation descendant of Grand Prince Wanpung who was the elder half-brother of [[King Taejo of Joseon]], the founder of [[Joseon|Joseon Kingdom]].\nHe is a member of the South Korean Presbyterian Church.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yoo Il-ho]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of South Korea]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chung Sye-kyun]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of South Korea}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Nak-yon}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Minjoo Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Seoul National University alumni]]\n[[Category:South Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:Yi clan of Jeonju]]\n[[Category:People from South Jeolla Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prime Minister of South Korea}}\n{{Korean name|Lee}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|name          = Lee Nak-yeon\n| native_name = {{nobold|\uc774\ub099\uc5f0}}\n| native_name_lang = ko\n|image         = South Korean Prime Minister Lee - 2017 (36235112603) (cropped).jpg\n|office2        = 41st [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]\n|president2     = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n|term_start2    = 31 May 2017\n|term_end2      = 14 January 2020\n|deputy2        = [[Kim Dong-yeon]]<br>[[Kim Sang-gon]]<br>[[Yoo Eun-hae]]<br>[[Hong Nam-ki]]\n|predecessor2   = [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]<br>[[Yoo Il-ho]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|successor2     = [[Chung Sye-kyun]]\n|office3        = [[Governor of South Jeolla Province]]\n|term_start3    = 1 July 2014\n|term_end3      = 10 May 2017\n|predecessor3   = Park Jun-young\n|successor3     = [[Kim Yung-rok]]\n|office         = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Korea|National Assembly]] <br>{{small|Elect}}\n|term_label     = Assuming office\n|term           = 30 May 2020\n|predecessor    = [[Chung Sye-kyun]]\n|successor      = \n|constituency   = [[Jongno-gu]]\n|term_start1    = 30 May 2000\n|term_end1      = 15 May 2014\n|predecessor1   = Kim In-gon\n|successor1     = Lee Gae-ho\n|constituency1  = [[Damyang County|Damyang]], [[Hampyeong County|Hampyeong]], [[Yeonggwang County|Yeonggwang]] and [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|12|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Yeonggwang County|Yeonggwang]], [[South Korea]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n|spouse         = [[Kim Suk-hee]]\n|children       = 1\n|signature      = Signature of Lee Nak-yeon.png\n|education      = [[Seoul National University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]])}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul = {{linktext|\uc774|\ub099|\uc5f0}}\n|hanja  = {{linktext|\u674e|\u6d1b|\u6df5}}\n|rr     = I Nak-yeon \n|mr     = Yi Nag-y\u014fn\n}}\n'''Lee Nak-yeon''' ({{korean|hangul=\uc774\ub099\uc5f0|hanja=\u674e\u6d1b\u6df5}}; born 20 December 1951),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star-profile.tistory.com/m/85|title=\uad6d\ubb34\ucd1d\ub9ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0 \ud504\ub85c\ud544|date=15 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.tip.daum.net/question/88036592|title=\uc804\ub0a8\ub3c4\uc9c0\uc0ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0\uc740 \uad6d\uc778\uc5d0\ub2f9\uc778\uac00??|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.co.kr/news/300049|title=\ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ub2f9\uc120 \ud6c4 \ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \uc815\ubd80 \uc774\ub099\uc5f0 \uc804\ub0a8\uc9c0\uc0ac \ucd1d\ub9ac \ub0b4\uc815 \uc131\ud5a5\uc740?|first=|last=\ud06c\ub9ac\uc2a4\ucc9c\ud22c\ub370\uc774|date=10 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref> also known as Lee Nak-yon, is a [[South Korea]]n politician who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of South Korea|41st]] [[Prime Minister of South Korea]].<ref name=\"ref1\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.arirang.co.kr/News/News_View.asp?nseq=203843|title=Korea's new president announces key Cabinet picks|website=Arirang|access-date=May 11, 2017}}</ref> He is also the longest serving prime minister of South Korea since the [[Constitution of South Korea]] was last revised in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191028001800315|title=Lee becomes longest-serving prime minister in S. Korea|last=\uae40\uc218\uc5f0|date=2019-10-28|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> He previously served as the governor of [[Jeollanam-do]] province.<ref name=ref1>{{cite web|language=Korean |url=http://mbn.mk.co.kr/pages/news/newsView.php?category=mbn00006&news_seq_no=3218706 |title=\u6587\ub300\ud1b5\ub839, \uad6d\ubb34\ucd1d\ub9ac \uc774\ub099\uc5f0\u00b7\uad6d\uc815\uc6d0\uc7a5 \uc11c\ud6c8\u00b7\ube44\uc11c\uc2e4\uc7a5 \uc784\uc885\uc11d\u00b7\uacbd\ud638\uc2e4\uc7a5 \uc8fc\uc601\ud6c8 \uc9c0\uba85 |publisher=Mbn.mk.co.kr |date=2017-05-10 |accessdate=2017-05-10}}</ref> Before serving as governor, he worked as a journalist for the ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' and served as a member of the [[National Assembly of Korea|National Assembly]] for four terms.\n\n== Early life and education==\nLee was born on December 20, 1951 in [[Yeonggwang County]] in [[South Jeolla Province]]. After graduating from [[Seoul National University]] with a degree in law, he worked as a journalist for the daily ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' newspaper until 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/05/11/2017051101354.html|title=Moon Taps South Jeolla Province Governor as New PM|access-date=2017-05-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nHe entered politics in 2000 \"based on his ties with former President [[Kim Dae-jung]] he formed while covering politics.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/05/10/0200000000AEN20170510004251315.html|title=(LEAD) (profile) Moon's premier pick is based in liberal stronghold, has broad political ties|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=2017-05-11|language=en}}</ref> Following his departure from the ''[[The Dong-a Ilbo|Dong-a Ilbo]]'' he was elected as a member of the [[National Assembly of Korea|National Assembly]] in 2000 and served for four terms.<ref name=\":0\" /> He also served as a spokesman for former President [[Roh Moo-hyun]] when he was the president-elect in 2002.<ref name=\"Korea\">[http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pad/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=229097 \"S. Jeolla governor tapped as PM nominee\"], Korea Times, May 10, 2017 .</ref>\n\nHe left office in the middle of his fourth term in 2014 to successfully run for governor of [[South Jeolla Province]].\n\n== Prime Minister ==\nOn May 10, 2017, he was nominated by [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Moon Jae-in]] to be the next [[Prime Minister of South Korea]], succeeding [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]. He left office as governor of the South Jeolla Province on the same day.\nHe is seen as having close ties with key Japanese politicians, having served many years as a senior officer in the [[Japan-Korea Parliamentarians' Union|Korea-Japan Parliamentarians' Union]]. Lee speaks fluent Japanese.<ref name=\"Nikkei\">[http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/South-Korean-prime-minister-pick-seen-as-point-man-on-Japan \"South Korean prime minister pick seen as point man on Japan\"], Nikkei Asian Review, May 11, 2017 .</ref> On June 25, Prime Minister Lee urged North Korea to release their prisoners. On July 27, Prime Minister Lee Nak-yeon, who is known to be knowledgeable about Japan, criticized the accord regarding \u2018comfort women\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20170727/p2a/00m/0na/017000c|title=Japan wary of S. Korea's growing opposition to 'comfort women' accord|date=27 July 2017|publisher=|via=Mainichi Daily News}}</ref> On August 16, Lee reacted negatively to calls for South Korea to possess nuclear weapons, saying the move would undermine Seoul's calls for North Korea to denuclearize, trigger a nuclear arms race and put the country under international sanctions. Reflecting such calls, the main opposition Liberty Korea Party adopted a demand for the redeployment of US tactical nuclear arms as its official party line during a general meeting of its lawmakers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170816000831#cb|title=PM negative about calls for Korea\u2018s nuclear armament|date=16 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On November 29, Lee raised concerns that cryptocurrencies were corrupting the youth of South Korea, remarking \u201cThere are cases in which young Koreans including students are jumping in to make quick money and virtual currencies are used in illegal activities like drug dealing or multi-level marketing for frauds\u201d.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Post-PM career ==\nIn [[2020 South Korean legislative election|2020 election]], Lee stood for [[Jongno District|Jongno]] constituency and defeated the [[United Future Party|UFP]] President [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 15 April 2020|title= [\ub2f9\uc120-\uc11c\uc6b8 \uc885\ub85c] \uc774\ub099\uc5f0, \u201c\uad6d\ub09c \uadf9\ubcf5\uc5d0 \ud63c\uc2e0 \ub178\ub825 \ud560 \uac83\u201d|url= http://cnews.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=202004152325409437d9fbed771_16|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!Year\n!Province\n!Party Affiliation\n!Votes \n!Percentage of votes\n!Results\n|-\n|16th National Assembly General Election\n|2000\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party (2000)]]\n|37,863\n|60.20%\n|Won\n|-\n|17th National Assembly General Election\n|2004\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party (2000)]]\n|30,123\n|55.28%\n|Won\n|-\n|18th National Assembly General Election\n|2008\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yougggwang, [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]] Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2008)|Democratic Party (2008)]] \n|42,950\n|67.93%\n|Won\n|-\n|19th National Assembly General Election\n|2012\n|[[South Jeolla Province|Jeonnam]] ([[Damyang County|Damyang]], [[Hampyeong County|Hampyong]], Yonggwang, [[Jangseong County|Jangseong]] Counties)\n|[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic United Party]] \n|63,887\n|77.32%\n|Won\n|-\n|Provincial Gubernatorial Election \n|2014\n|[[South Jeolla Province|South Jeolla]] \n|[[New Politics Alliance for Democracy]] (NPAD)\n|755,036\n|77.96%\n|Won\n|-\n|21st National Assembly General Election\n|2020\n|[[Seoul|Jongno]]\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|54,902\n|58.38%\n|Won\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nLee is married. Lee Nak-yon's bongwan belongs to the Jeonju Yi clan, which makes him part of the royal Yi family. He is also the 22nd-generation descendant of Grand Prince Wanpung who was the elder half-brother of [[King Taejo of Joseon]], the founder of [[Joseon|Joseon Kingdom]].\nHe is a member of the South Korean Presbyterian Church.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yoo Il-ho]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of South Korea]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chung Sye-kyun]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of South Korea}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Nak-yon}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Minjoo Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Seoul National University alumni]]\n[[Category:South Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:Yi clan of Jeonju]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "says it in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Nak-yeon"